The Standards Organisation of Nigeria (SON) has commenced the regulation of conformity assessment  to establish registration and regulation for National Standards, Standard Marks, Certification Systems and Licences. Its Director-General, Farouk Salim, spoke at the inauguration of an Impartiality Committee to monitor and guide the National Registry of Conformity Assessment Practitioners (NRCAP) in Abuja. He noted that the committee is set up to ensure that management system standard implementation, product testing and certification are in compliance with international best practice.   Chinese Yuan strengthens to 6.3752 against USD Wednesday     Russia-Ukraine conflict: Trade recovery at risk, warns…     World Bank: poverty to rise over high food prices, currency…   This, he said, would include assessment and registration of competencies of management system standards and auditors, quality inspectors, management system certification bodies, management system consultants, management systems training institutions, testing laboratories and quality inspection bodies. He assured that the scheme was to establish a directory of verified and registered conformity assessment practitioners for all laboratories, management systems auditors, trainers, consultants, inspectors as well as inspection and certification bodies. The DG noted that the appointment of an Impartiality Committee was in line with international  practices to guarantee fairness and transparency in the NRCAP Unit. “The constitution of the Impartiality Committee was based on the attributes of due professional care, independence, confidentiality, integrity, proven experience in quality assurance and conformity assessment practice demonstrated over the years by the members in the course of their active work life, in addition to the existing strategic collaboration and partnership that SON shares with the various organisations that they represent,” he said.